<DOC><DOCNO> AP890912-0156 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 2001EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-Brites     09-12 0183</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Brites,0188</SECOND><HEAD>Brite and Brief</HEAD><DATELINE>SAN BERNARDINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Darla Schardein was born during arush to the hospital, but not in the back seat of a car. Theimpatient newborn chose the cargo bay of a helicopter as herdelivery room.   Dawn Schardein, 28, gave birth to 5-pound, 9{-ounce Darla earlyMonday after sudden labor during a visit with friends in Sun City, aremote Riverside County city served by a hospital lacking amaternity ward.   Her husband, Mike, 29, rushed her to Menifee Valley MedicalCenter in Sun City, about 70 miles southeast of downtown LosAngeles, where quick thinking by emergency room workers resulted inthe calling of an air ambulance to take Mrs. Schardein to SanBernardino, about 30 miles away.   The baby was delivered just as the helicopter set down near SaintBernardine Medical Center, said flight nurse Russel West.   ``Just as we went down, we were actually landing, she was born,''West said. ``It was a very smooth, rapid delivery ... A nice,healthy baby girl.''   Mother, baby and flight crew were all doing fine.</TEXT></DOC>